library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)


# A scatter plot comparing Avg_HH_size with immigrant population fraction
p1 <- ggplot(data = joined_data,
             mapping = aes(x = Avg_HH_size.x,
                           y = (immig.pop.x / total.pop.x))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Average Household Size (2016)",
       y = "Percent Immigrant",
       title = "Scatter Plot: Immigrant Population Fraction vs. Avg Household Size (2016)")

p1

# Assuming you want to compare Avg_HH_size in 2016 (x-axis) with immigrant population fraction
threshold <- 2.5  # Adjust the threshold as needed

p2 <- p1 + geom_point(data = subset(joined_data,
                                    Avg_HH_size.x > threshold),
                      mapping = aes(x = Avg_HH_size.x,
                                    y = (immig.pop.x / total.pop.x)), color = "greenyellow") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(color = "High Avg Household Size CMAs",
       x = "Average Household Size (2016)",
       y = "Percent Immigrant",
       title = "Immigrants and Average Household Size",
       caption = "Source: Canadian Census Data, 2016")

p2

library(ggrepel)

# Compare Avg_HH_size in 2016 (x-axis) with immigrant population fraction (%)
threshold <- 2.5

p3 <- p2 + geom_text_repel(data = subset(joined_data,
                                         Avg_HH_size.x > threshold),
                           mapping = aes(x = Avg_HH_size.x,
                                         y = (immig.pop.x / total.pop.x),
                                         label = `Region Name`),
                           size = 2)

p3 + theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

cat("The graph presents the relationship between the change in immigrant population fraction from 2016 to 2021 (y-axis) and the average household size in 2016 (x-axis) for various Canadian Metropolitan Areas (CMAs). Each point on the scatter plot represents a CMA, with the size of the point indicating the magnitude of the change. Regions with average household sizes greater than 2.5 are in the green color. The visualization provide good insights into how variations in average household size may be associated with the percentage in immigrant population over the year 2016. The audience can easily identify CMAs that exhibit notable region with significant changes in immigrant fractions and explore potential connections with average household size.")
The graph presents the relationship between the change in immigrant population fraction from 2016 to 2021 (y-axis) and the average household size in 2016 (x-axis) for various Canadian Metropolitan Areas (CMAs). Each point on the scatter plot represents a CMA, with the size of the point indicating the magnitude of the change. Regions with average household sizes greater than 2.5 are in the green color. The visualization provide good insights into how variations in average household size may be associated with the percentage in immigrant population over the year 2016. The audience can easily identify CMAs that exhibit notable region with significant changes in immigrant fractions and explore potential connections with average household size.
